) (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Bedroom tax") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money")) "Council tax") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Poverty") (pubDate nil "Sun, 31 Mar 2013 23:01:00 GMT") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2013/apr/01/every-welfare-cut-listed") (dc:creator nil "Patrick Butler") (dc:subject nil "News") (dc:date nil "2013-04-02T10:14:34Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "406391103") (media:keywords nil "UK news, Welfare, Society, Poverty, Bedroom tax, Benefits, Council tax") (media:content ((height . "84") (lang . " ") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/pictures/2011/3/29/1301415517896/A-march-in-protest-at-gov-002.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Peter Macdiarmid/Getty Images") (media:description nil "A march in protest at government cuts passes parliament in London on its way to Hyde Park. Photograph: Peter Macdiarmid/Getty Images")) (media:content ((height . "276") (lang . " ") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Education/Pix/pictures/2011/3/29/1301415526144/A-march-in-protest-at-gov-006.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Peter Macdiarmid/Getty Images") (media:description nil "A march in protest at government cuts passes parliament in London on its way to Hyde Park. Photograph: Peter Macdiarmid/Getty Images"))) (item nil (title nil "Every Doctor Who villain since 1963 - as a spreadsheet and visualised") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2010/jul/16/doctor-who-villains-list") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/70364?ns=guardian&pageName=Graphic%3Adoctor-who-villains-list%3A1427220&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Doctor+Who+%28TV+and+radio%29%2CCulture%2CScience+fiction+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media%2CTV&c6=Simon+Rogers&c7=2010%2F07%2F16+12%3A34&c8=1427220&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Datablog%2CTV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Every+Doctor+Who+villain+since+1963&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FDoctor+Who\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The Doctor has fought more than 400 villains and monsters. Find out who they are - and which appeared most<br />• <a href=\"#data\">Get the data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2010/aug/20/doctor-who-time-travel-information-is-beautiful\">Information is Beautiful on the Doctor's time travels</a></p><p><strong>• Includes villains' appearances from all episodes up to <em> The Bells of Saint John</em></strong></p><p>Doctor Who is back, with more villains for us to add to the list.</p><p><a href=\"http://manyeyes.alphaworks.ibm.com/manyeyes/visualizations/doctor-who-villains\">inspired by the work of xxnapoleonsolo on Many Eyes</a>, we tried to put together the definitive list of every Doctor Who villain and monster - ever. <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2010/jul/20/doctor-whos-enemies\">We had no idea there were so many</a>. Here's our Tableau visualisation of them so far.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p>We've been adding loads of new creatures and people - thanks to your suggestions - and we probably still have some more to go. </p><p>So, here's a list of all the Doctor Who villains since the very first episode in 1963. Whether it's to help you put your bet on what will make a reappearance next series or just to satisfy hard-core Whovians, hopefully this will help out.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p>The chart however doesn't include villains exclusively in Doctor Who books, audio books and spin-off shows - only the televised serials and only enemies, as opposed to protagonists. See the comments below for more details.</p><p>We're bound to have missed someone - or even got some details wrong. So let us know in the comments field below - and tell us if you do anything with the <a href=\"#data\">data</a>. We've extended the comments date so we can keep going with the new series.</p><p>Which was your favourite? Download the data and let us know what you can do with it.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><a name=\"data\"></p><h2>Download the data</h2><p></a><br />• <a href=\"http://spreadsheets.google.com/ccc?key=0AonYZs4MzlZbdHJNSVh6clE4MVR4OHhqZWs4WGpSZlE&hl=en\">DATA: download the full datasheet</a></p><h2>More data</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data\">More data journalism and data visualisations from the Guardian</a></p><h2>World government data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world-government-data\">Search the world's government data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Development and aid data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store/global-development-data/search?q=\">Search the world's global development data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Can you do something with this data?</h2><p>• <strong>Flickr</strong> Please post your visualisations and mash-ups on our <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/groups/1115946@N24/\">Flickr group</a><br />• Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:data@guardian.co.uk\">data@guardian.co.uk</a></p><p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/page/2009/jun/17/1\">Get the A-Z of data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store\">More at the Datastore directory</a></strong><br /><strong>• <a href=\"http://twitter.com/guardiandata\">Follow us on Twitter</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/Guardian-data/155291341187950\">Like us on Facebook</a></strong></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/doctor-who\">Doctor Who</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/science-fiction\">Science fiction</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/simonrogers\">Simon Rogers</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" /><img width='1' height='1' src='http://guardian.co.uk.feedsportal.com/c/34708/f/643782/s/2a2bc672/mf.gif' border='0'/><div class='mf-viral'><table border='0'><tr><td valign='middle'><a href=\"http://share.feedsportal.com/viral/sendEmail.cfm?lang=en&title=Every+Doctor+Who+villain+since+1963+-+as+a+spreadsheet+and+visualised&link=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.guardian.co.uk%2Fnews%2Fdatablog%2F2010%2Fjul%2F16%2Fdoctor-who-villains-list\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://res3.feedsportal.com/images/emailthis2.gif\" border=\"0\" /></a></td></tr></table></div><br/><br/><a href=\"http://da.feedsportal.com/r/161990811447/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2a2bc672/a2.htm\"><img src=\"http://da.feedsportal.com/r/161990811447/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2a2bc672/a2.img\" border=\"0\"/></a><img width=\"1\" height=\"1\" src=\"http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/161990811447/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2a2bc672/a2t.img\" border=\"0\"/>") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Science fiction") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Doctor Who") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (pubDate nil "Sat, 30 Mar 2013 23:30:00 GMT") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2010/jul/16/doctor-who-villains-list") (dc:creator nil "Simon Rogers") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-03-30T23:45:40Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "364946171") (media:keywords nil "Doctor Who, Culture, Science fiction, Television") (media:content ((height . "84") (lang . " ") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/maps_and_graphs/2010/7/16/1279279938882/Doctor-Who-gold-Dalek-002.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Rex Features/Rex Features") (media:description nil "Daleks have appeared more times than any other Doctor Who villain. Photograph: Rex Features")) (media:content ((height . "276") (lang . " ") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/maps_and_graphs/2010/7/16/1279279944060/Doctor-Who-gold-Dalek-006.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Rex Features/Rex Features") (media:description nil "Daleks have appeared more times than any other Doctor Who villain. Photograph: Rex Features")) (media:content ((height . "276") (lang . " ") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/3/29/1364565816501/Doctor-Who---The-Bells-of-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "BBC/Adrian Rogers") (media:description nil "Jenna-Louise Coleman as Clara and Matt Smith as the Doctor in The Bells of St John. Photograph: BBC/Adrian Rogers")) (media:content ((height . "276") (lang . " ") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/3/29/1364547135455/who460.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Guardian") (media:description nil "Doctor Who: a graphic history. Click image to see it"))) (item nil (title nil "Homes in East London are 'unhappiest' in UK") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2013/mar/27/homes-east-london-unhappiest-in-uk") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/8003?ns=guardian&pageName=Data%3Ahomes-east-london-unhappiest-in-uk%3A1886214&ch=News&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=UK+news%2CProperty+%28Money+-+UK+consumer%29%2CHappiness+indices%2CRightmove+%28Business%29%2CSociety&c5=Society+Weekly%2CUnclassified%2CBusiness+Markets%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CProperty+Mortgages+and+Interest+Rates&c6=Mona+Chalabi&c7=2013%2F03%2F27+03%3A12&c8=1886214&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Datablog&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Homes+in+East+London+%27unhappiest%27+in+UK&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FNews%2Fblog%2FDatablog\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Which towns are considered the happiest places to live? UK property site Rightmove have attempted to find out in a nationwide survey<br />• <a href=\"#data\">Download the data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data\">More data journalism and data visualisations from the Guardian</a></p><p>Whether it was 'space', 'investment', 'safety' or quite simply 'contentment', homes in East London report the lowest levels of happiness in the UK according to research published today by property website<a href=\"http://www.rightmove.co.uk/news/articles/rightmove-news/happy-at-home-index-london\"> Rightmove</a>. </p><p>The survey of almost 40,000 people also found that nine of the 10 'unhappiest' places to live were to be found in Greater London. Harrogate in Yorkshire came top of the list as the <a href=\"http://www.guprod.gnl/news/datablog/2013/mar/27/uk-towns-happiness-ranking\">'happiest town' to live in in the UK</a>.</p><p>Carlisle, which was considered the happiest town in 2012 has since dropped to 19th place. Meanwhile, towns in Greater London continue to languish at the bottom of the chart. East London, which received the lowest score in 2012, again had the fewest respondents reporting happiness in 2013. </p><p><strong>How do you define happiness?</strong></p><p>Rightmove's <a href=\"http://www.rightmove.co.uk/news/files/2013/03/Rightmove-Happy-At-Home-Index-2013.pdf\">approach</a> was to ask people in 110 UK towns to what extent they agreed with 12 statements ranging from 'I often feel unsafe in the community in which I live' to 'I do not worry about the value of my property'. </p><p>But not all of the statements in the survey necessarily reflect upon towns. For example, the first statement 'on the whole, the décor and furnishings in my home are to my liking' might be more indicative of the socio-economic background of the individual completing the survey, than of the town under scrutiny. As it turns out, Cleveland in the North East comes top for residents satisfaction with their own décor, but ranks 64th overall in the index. </p><p>Similarly, a negative response to the statement 'generally, I feel relaxed when I am at home' may say more about family life than the town in which the respondent lives. Here again, the correlation between this response and the overall results is relatively weak. </p><p>Harrogate which comes first overall, ranks in 79th place for residents feeling relaxed at home. It is also not clear whether the 40,000 respondents were drawn in equal measure for the 110 towns included in the survey. Clearly, if five people were asked their views on Stockport (2nd place) and 1,000 people were asked about their homes in Croydon (109th place), the findings would be highly skewed. </p><p>There was however a strong correlation between responses on 'neighbourliness' (captured by Rightmove in the statement 'I enjoy spending time in the area in which I live') and a town's overall score. In Greater London where the lowest scores were recorded, respondents were inclined to strongly disagree with this statement.</p><p>Do you agree with these rankings for your town? Contribute to the debate by adding your comments below. You can download the full results from the spreadsheet.</p><h2>Data summary</h2><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a name=\"data\"></p><h2>Download the data</h2><p></a></p><p>• <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0At6CC4x_yBnMdGRMZVdlbV9HM3BqVFJHMlFSOF82bkE&usp=sharing\">DATA: download the full spreadsheet</a><br /><strong>• SOURCE: </strong><a href=\"http://www.rightmove.co.uk/news/articles/rightmove-news/happy-at-home-index-2013\">Rightmove</a></p><h2>NEW! Buy our book</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.guardianbookshop.co.uk/BerteShopWeb/viewProduct.do?ISBN=9780571301614&INTCMP=mic_929\">• Facts are Sacred: the power of data </a></p><h2>More open data</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data\">Data journalism and data visualisations from the Guardian</a></p><h2>World government data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world-government-data\">Search the world's government data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Development and aid data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store/global-development-data/search?q=\">Search the world's global development data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Can you do something with this data?</h2><p>• <strong>Flickr</strong> Please post your visualisations and mash-ups on our <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/groups/1115946@N24/\">Flickr group</a><br />• Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:data@guardian.co.uk\">data@guardian.co.uk</a></p><p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/page/2009/jun/17/1\">Get the A-Z of data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store\">More at the Datastore directory</a></strong><br /><strong>• <a href=\"http://twitter.com/GuardianData\">Follow us on Twitter</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/Guardian-data/155291341187950\">Like us on Facebook</a></strong></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/property\">Property</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/happiness-indices\">Happiness indices</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/rightmove\">Rightmove</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/mona-chalabi\">Mona Chalabi</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" /><img width='1' height='1' src='http://guardian.co.uk.feedsportal.com/c/34708/f/643782/s/2a0e0128/mf.gif' border='0'/><div class='mf-viral'><table border='0'><tr><td valign='middle'><a href=\"http://share.feedsportal.com/viral/sendEmail.cfm?lang=en&title=Homes+in+East+London+are+%27unhappiest%27+in+UK&link=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.guardian.co.uk%2Fnews%2Fdatablog%2F2013%2Fmar%2F27%2Fhomes-east-london-unhappiest-in-uk\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://res3.feedsportal.com/images/emailthis2.gif\" border=\"0\" /></a></td></tr></table></div><br/><br/><a href=\"http://da.feedsportal.com/r/161990697992/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2a0e0128/kg/350/a2.htm\"><img src=\"http://da.feedsportal.com/r/161990697992/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2a0e0128/kg/350/a2.img\" border=\"0\"/></a><img width=\"1\" height=\"1\" src=\"http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/161990697992/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2a0e0128/kg/350/a2t.img\" border=\"0\"/>") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money")) "Property") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Society") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Rightmove") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "UK news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Happiness indices") (pubDate nil "Wed, 27 Mar 2013 15:12:00 GMT") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2013/mar/27/homes-east-london-unhappiest-in-uk") (dc:creator nil "Mona Chalabi") (dc:subject nil "News") (dc:date nil "2013-03-27T15:54:35Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "406322180") (media:keywords nil "UK news, Property, Happiness indices, Rightmove, Society") (media:content ((height . "84") (lang . " ") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/5/15/1337103097843/Council-estate-in-Poplar--003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "David Levene/David Levene") (media:description nil "Robin Hood Gardens, a council housing estate in Poplar, Eeast London. 'Young people from less well-off backgrounds risk losing out on opportunities for better higher education and jobs' Photograph: David Levene")) (media:content ((height . "276") (lang . " ") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/5/15/1337103104852/Council-estate-in-Poplar--008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "David Levene/David Levene") (media:description nil "East London has been named the 'unhappiest' place in the UK in a survey measuring how the British public feels about where they live. Photograph: David Levene"))) (item nil (title nil "UK GDP since 1955") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2009/nov/25/gdp-uk-1948-growth-economy") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/35473?ns=guardian&pageName=Graphic%3Agdp-uk-1948-growth-economy%3A1176842&ch=Business&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Economic+growth+%28GDP%29+UK%2CEconomic+policy%2CEconomics+%28Business%29%2CQuantitative+easing+%28Business%29%2CFinancial+crisis+%28Business%29%2CBusiness%2CUK+news%2CGovernment+data+%28Politics%29%2COffice+for+National+Statistics+ONS%2CGeneral+election+2010&c5=Credit+Crunch%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CBusiness+Markets&c6=Simon+Rogers&c7=2009%2F03%2F09+05%3A00&c8=1176842&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Datablog&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=UK+GDP+since+1955&c66=Business&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FBusiness%2FBusiness%2FEconomic+growth+%28GDP%29\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Gross domestic product is the economic output of Britain. See how it has changed over time<br />• <a href=\"#data\">Get the data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/interactive/2012/sep/27/recessions-compared-1930-2008\">Interactive chart: How does this recession compare?</a><br />• <a href=\"#chart\">Chart: GDP change since 2008</a></p><p><strong></strong></p><p>The possibility of a triple-dip recession seems to have inched closer as GDP for the last three months of 2012 was confirmed to have dropped by 0.3%. If the economy shrinks again in the first quarter of this year, that will plunge the UK into its third recession in the past five years, an unprecedented triple-dip.</p><p>You can find out who gets <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2012/oct/25/pre-release-access-good-news-david-cameron\">access to this data early too by clicking here.</a></p><p>The ONS explains the data as follows:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p><br />• Household final consumption expenditure increased by 0.4% in volume terms in the latest quarter revised up from the 0.2% increase previously estimated<br />• Among the main contributors to the decrease in GDP in the latest quarter were gross fixed capital formation which fell by 0.2% in volume terms and the £6.0 billion net trade deficit, which follows a £5.3 billion net trade deficit in the previous quarter<br />• GDP in volume terms increased by 0.2% when comparing the fourth quarter of 2012 with the fourth quarter of 2011. Between the years 2011 and 2012, GDP in volume terms increased by 0.3%<br />• The households' saving ratio was estimated to be 7.1% in 2012, the highest since the 1997 estimate of 8.1%<br />• Real household disposable income increased by 2.1% between 2011 and 2012. This is the highest growth since 2003 when it rose by 2.7%<br />• The largest contributions to the increases in the households' saving ratio and real household disposable income were an estimated £20.1 billion increase in wages and salaries in 2012 compared with 2011</p></blockquote><p>A technical recession is defined as two or more consecutive quarters of economic decline. That means the UK is now on course for its third recession in four years.<a name=\"chart\"></a></p><p>The data we have gathered shows percentage change in GDP going back to 1955 by quarter, we have a spreadsheet to download that shows GDP in cash, ie what it was that year not adjusted for inflation, total inflation-adjusted figures and per capita inflation adjusted figures.</p><p>The figures show how recessions compare - thanks to the <a href=\"http://www.niesr.ac.uk/\">National Institute of Economic and Social Research</a> for the data.</p><p>As several of our posters below have pointed out, there's <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2009/mar/24/g20-economics\">more to life than GDP</a> – but here are the latest GDP figures from the ONS for you to explore.</p><h2>Data summary</h2><p><strong></strong></p><p><a name=\"data\"></p><h2>Download the full data</h2><p></a></p><p><a href=\"http://spreadsheets.google.com/ccc?key=phNtm3LmDZEO_Y5Udz-7uSw\">DATA: UK GDP since 1948</a></p><p>• SOURCE: <a href=\"http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/gva/gross-domestic-product--preliminary-estimate/q4-2012/tsd---preliminary-estimate-of-gdp-q4-2012.html\">ONS</a></p><h2>More data</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data\">More data journalism and data visualisations from the Guardian</a></p><h2>World government data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world-government-data\">Search the world's government data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Development and aid data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store/global-development-data/search?q=\">Search the world's global development data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Can you do something with this data?</h2><p>• <strong>Flickr</strong> Please post your visualisations and mash-ups on our <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/groups/1115946@N24/\">Flickr group</a><br />• Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:data@guardian.co.uk\">data@guardian.co.uk</a></p><p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/page/2009/jun/17/1\">Get the A-Z of data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store\">More at the Datastore directory</a></strong><br /><strong>• <a href=\"http://twitter.com/guardiandata\">Follow us on Twitter</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/Guardian-data/155291341187950\">Like us on Facebook</a></strong></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/economicgrowth\">Economic growth (GDP)</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/economy\">Economic policy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/economics\">Economics</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/quantitative-easing\">Quantitative easing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/financial-crisis\">Financial crisis</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/government-data\">Government data</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/office-for-national-statistics\">Office for National Statistics</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/general-election-2010\">General election 2010</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/simonrogers\">Simon Rogers</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" /><img width='1' height='1' src='http://guardian.co.uk.feedsportal.com/c/34708/f/643782/s/2a0b98ae/mf.gif' border='0'/><div class='mf-viral'><table border='0'><tr><td valign='middle'><a href=\"http://share.feedsportal.com/viral/sendEmail.cfm?lang=en&title=UK+GDP+since+1955&link=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.guardian.co.uk%2Fnews%2Fdatablog%2F2009%2Fnov%2F25%2Fgdp-uk-1948-growth-economy\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://res3.feedsportal.com/images/emailthis2.gif\" border=\"0\" /></a></td></tr></table></div><br/><br/><a href=\"http://da.feedsportal.com/r/161990707609/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2a0b98ae/a2.htm\"><img src=\"http://da.feedsportal.com/r/161990707609/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2a0b98ae/a2.img\" border=\"0\"/></a><img width=\"1\" height=\"1\" src=\"http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/161990707609/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2a0b98ae/a2t.img\" border=\"0\"/>") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Economic growth (GDP)") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "Office for National Statistics") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Quantitative easing") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Government data") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "General election 2010") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Economics") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "UK news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Economic policy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Financial crisis") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/business")) "Business") (pubDate nil "Wed, 27 Mar 2013 10:40:00 GMT") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2009/nov/25/gdp-uk-1948-growth-economy") (dc:creator nil "Simon Rogers") (dc:subject nil "Business") (dc:date nil "2013-03-27T11:30:45Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "343973673") (media:keywords nil "Economic growth (GDP), Economic policy, Economics, Quantitative easing, Financial crisis, Business, UK news, Government data, Office for National Statistics, General election 2010") (media:content ((height . "84") (lang . " ") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/maps_and_graphs/2011/05/26/RECESSION_CHART84.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Guardian") (media:description nil "GDP change over the last big recessions"))) (item nil (title nil "Devolution and Westminster: How productive are non-English MPs?") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2013/mar/27/how-productive-non-english-mps") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/65313?ns=guardian&pageName=GUK%3AData%3Ahow-productive-non-english-mps%3A1884291&ch=News&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=UK+news%2CPolitics%2CScotland+%28News%29%2CNorthern+Ireland+%28News%29%2CWales+%28News%29%2CConservatives+tories+tory+party%2CLiberal+Democrats+Lib+dems%2CLabour%2CSNP+%28Politics%29%2CSinn+Fein&c5=Not+commercially+useful&c6=Severin+Carrell&c7=2013%2F03%2F27+08%3A00&c8=1884291&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Datablog%2CScotland+blog&c47=UK&c65=Devolution+and+Westminster%3A+how+productive+are+non-English+MPs%3F&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FNews%2Fblog%2FDatablog\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">UK ministers are studying proposals to limit the voting rights of Scottish, Welsh and Northern Irish MPs, to give England's MPs greater influence over English legislation. What do the numbers show us about how busy these MPs are?<br /><br />• <a href=\"#data\">Download the data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data\">More data journalism and data visualisations from the Guardian</a></p><p>Ministers in the UK government are considering whether to take action on one of the most sensitive and potentially contentious issues at Westminster: limiting the rights of MPs from Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland to vote and decide on \"England only\" legislation.</p><p>But that in turn raises an equally thorny issue: if non-English MPs are to have a more restricted role in the Commons, are as many needed? Are they as busy as they once were? Scottish Tories are privately suggesting the numbers of Scottish MPs might need to be cut: a move which would most likely reduce the number of Labour MPs at Westminster the most.</p><p>There was evidence in the earlier years of devolution that MPs from other parts of the UK were often much less busy, but a new Guardian survey suggests that is no longer true: Scottish and Welsh MPs in particular are amongst the busiest at Westminster – particularly the Scottish National party. Compared to the early years of devolution, when MPs had not yet adjusted, today's non-England MPs are highly active.</p><p>It is a debate best known as the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2012/jan/17/what-is-west-lothian-question\">West Lothian question</a> – posed in 1977 by the then Labour MP for West Lothian, Tam Dalyell. </p><p>A critic of devolution of Westminster's law-making powers to the proposed Scottish assembly, Dalyell conundrum was this: why, under devolution, Scottish MPs could still vote on English policies while English MPs could not vote on devolved Scottish affairs?</p><p>Variants of this question have been around since the late 1800s, tied then to proposals for Irish home rule. But, after 14 years of devolution of wide-ranging and increasing powers to the Scottish and Welsh legislatures, and the successful reformation of Northern Ireland's powerful assembly, that question is still very live.</p><p>On Monday, <a href=\"http://tmc.independent.gov.uk/report-of-the-commission-on-the-consequences-of-devolution-for-the-house-of-commons/\">McKay Commission inquiry</a> set up by UK ministers stated that an answer to the West Lothian question was needed, to ensure the Commons better reflected the specific interests of England, given that Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland now have domestic legislatures controlling large areas of policy and law-making.</p><p>While it rejected cutting the number of non-England MPs on principle, as that would undermine Westminster's role as the ultimate law-making body for the UK, it recommended that new measures and policies were put in place to ensure that in future, England-only bills were framed by only MPs from English seats. They would not have a veto to overrule the whole parliament, but the basic principle ought to be \"<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2013/mar/25/english-only-votes-legislation-commission\">English votes for English laws</a>\".</p><p>McKay stated: \"The status quo clearly cannot be sustained. Our proposals retain the right of a UK-wide majority to make the final decisions where they believe UK interests or those of a part of the UK other than England should prevail. We expect that governments will prefer compromise to conflict.\"</p><p>The Guardian survey has used three core activities in the Commons to compare how active MPs from the different nations are: voting, participating in debates and placing written parliamentary questions.</p><p>These three tests – the most visible of activities – have given us a snapshot picture of how busy MPs from the different parts of the UK have been at Westminster. We used data from <a href=\"http://www.theyworkforyou.com/\">theyworkforyou.com</a> on how many questions they asked and debates they spoke in for the year from 1 February 2012, and figures from <a href=\"http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/\">publicwhip.org.uk</a> for every vote since the 2010 general election.</p><p>It was designed to test how devolution of often significant legal and policy-making powers to the three devolved legislatures in Edinburgh, Cardiff and Belfast has reduced or changed the workload and work rate of MPs from those nations and regions.</p><p>The Guardian's study has found Scottish and Welsh MPs are often as active as their English counterparts – in some case more so. The results for Northern Ireland are more complicated: its five Sinn Fein MPs as supporters of a reunited Ireland, do not take up their seats on principle. Even so, the performance of Northern Irish MPs is very mixed.</p><p>Our survey, which captured every vote in since the 2010 election and all debates and parliament questions for the last year, gives a snapshot comparison of how national groups of MPs behave. It has found that:</p><blockquote><p>1. Scottish MPs voted on average in 65% of all votes, and Welsh MPs in 73%, compared to 75% of votes by English MPs on average. This is narrower gap than 10 years ago, perhaps reflecting the significance of UK-wide policies such as welfare, the economy, and defence, and the much tighter political balance in the Commons, which means votes can be closer.</p><p>2. The six Scottish National party MPs, who have a largely observed policy not to vote on bills which have no direct impact on Scotland, only took part in 47.6% of votes.</p><p>3. Northern Irish MPs, even excluding the five abstentionist Sinn Fein MPs who refuse on principle to take their seats at Westminster, only took part in 45% of all votes compared to 76% by English MPs or 65% by Scottish MPs.</p><p>This could reflect Stormont's far greater degree of control over domestic policy in Northern Ireland, which includes welfare and pensions. Even so, they spoke in 57 debates last year on average, against 37 for English MPs.</p><p>4. SNP, Welsh and Northern Irish MPs were – on average – more likely to speak in parliamentary debates last year: SNP MPs took part in 44 debates on average, against an average of 37 debates for English MPs. Welsh MPs spoke in 43.7 debates. But Northern Irish MPs spoke the most: excluding the four Sinn Fein abstainers, they took part in 57 debates each on average.</p><p>5. And SNP MPs – now repeatedly probing the UK government over independence-related issues – were, as a group, again top of the chart for asking parliamentary questions.</p><p>On average, the six SNP MPs asked 131 questions last year, because Angus Robertson, the SNP Westminster leader and defence spokesman, tabled 345 Pqs, with Mike Weir putting down 174 and Eilidh Whiteford 113. This average was nearly double the Scottish average of just under 70 questions and well above the English average of 55 PQ.s</p><p>6. Welsh MPs were also very active with parliamentary questions: they averaged 76.5 each in the year from February 2012 and 2013.</p><p>7. Some of the overall totals are skewed by extremely active individual MPs. For example, the Scottish MP Tom Greatrex, a shadow Labour energy minister, asked 515 PQ.s, while the Welsh Labour backbencher Chris Ruane asked 601 PQ.s – the record in our snapshot survey.</p><p>By comparison, the median or midpoint number for Pqs tabled by Scottish MPs is 34 and 32 for Welsh MPs, against 30 for English MPs.</p></blockquote><p>The West Lothian question leapt to life several times under Tony Blair's Labour government: some Tory MPs, including senior figures such as former leader William Hague, Ken Clarke and Sir Malcolm Rifkind, argue it is wrong for Scottish, Welsh and Northern Irish MPs to have undue control over bills and policies only affecting England.</p><p>The McKay inquiry stated that \"the political resonance of the West Lothian question is at its greatest\" when a UK government uses MPs from outside England to control the Commons, to outvote English opposition MPs.</p><p>The commission said these occasions are very rare: it has not happened in the post-devolution era and previously only between 1964 and 66, and briefly in early 1974, when England returned a Tory majority and Labour needed Scottish and Welsh backbenchers to force through legislation.</p><p>The commission did not mention that in 1965, Ulster unionist MPs allied with the Tory opposition to vote down Harold Wilson's plan to nationalise the steel industry: he was furious, as there was no steel industry in Northern Ireland.</p><p>There is a second scenario: where a government in power has used MPs from non-English seats to overcome a rebellion by its own backbenchers on English or English and Welsh legislation.</p><p>This happened twice for Labour since devolution situation, over foundation hospitals and tuition fees, when Scottish backbenchers voted en masse in favour of English and Welsh measures opposed by many English Labour MPs, saving Tony Blair's bills.</p><p>In parallel with these debates, researchers with University College London's constitution unit and think tanks found evidence that Scottish MPs caught up in the immediate post-devolution period were less busy but also often behaved as if devolution had not occurred.</p><p>Guy Lodge, a leading devolution analyst now with the Institute for Public Policy Research, and Oonagh Gay, found that Scottish MPs took part in fewer votes between 1999 and 2001. Lodge did a further study which found that in 2002-03, Scottish MPs were still putting questions to ministers with much less or no direct relevance to Scottish affairs, including the Home Office, transport and culture.</p><p>A study by Akash Paun, published in the constitution unit's \"The State of the Nations 2008\", found that in 2006 English Labour backbenchers spent far more on postage than their Scottish and Welsh counterparts: £4,137 versus £2,866 by Scottish backbenchers and £2,773 by Welsh. (The overall differential was lower: £3,633 on average for all English MPs versus £2,885 for Scottish MPs and £2,555 for Welsh.)</p><p>Paun also found that in 2004 English MPs did an average of 31.8 hours on constituency and local work, versus 24.4hrs by Scottish MPs and 27.6 by Welsh.</p><p>Compared to MPs moulded in the pre-devolution era when the Commons controlled all the UK's policies, devolution analysts such as Alan Trench and senior figures in the UK parties believe that MPs from devolved areas have adapted. They now have a better understanding of how to make Westminster work for them, when half their constituency work was gone.</p><p>The latest generation of MPs, particularly those newly elected in May 2010, are said to be more aware of the significant role they can play in the Commons on reserved powers, like the economy, welfare, trade and defence. Their constituency workload is much reduced: so they switch to UK level politics and policy.</p><p>(Welsh MPs do have more reserved powers to work on: the Home Office in London, for instance, still controls policing and courts in Wales. It does not do so in Scotland.)</p><p>But perhaps more significantly, Scottish and Welsh MPs are more active and visible in the Commons because the Tories are in power. As Scotland and Wales tend to elect proportionately more Labour MPs and have strong nationalist parties, so the Commons becomes their main battleground. Likewise, when the Tories were in opposition, the power and influence of non-England MPs at Westminster was a source of irritation and grievance.</p><p>In 2010, Scotland elected 41 Labour MPs out of 59, while Wales returned 26 Labour MPs out of 41. When Labour was in government these backbenchers were able to influence policy and get things done through direct contact with ministers. Any questions could be raised with a letter or a quiet word.</p><p>With Labour now in opposition: using parliamentary questions and debates is the main method for challenging the government. Envigorated by Alex Salmond's control of the Scottish parliament and next year's independence referendum, the SNP's six MPs are also very active, as this survey has shown.</p><p>If Alex Salmond's Scottish National party and the pro-independence movement loses the referendum on 18 September 2014, devolution of powers to Holyrood is expected to accelerate, which could in turn raise fresh questions about the role and number of non-English MPs in the Commons. If Salmond wins, this question is moot for Scotland: the SNP will have decisively answered the West Lothian question. For Wales, however, an independent Scotland could accelerate devolution to Cardiff.</p><p>After 2015, Labour, the Tories and the Liberal Democrats are all considering an increase in Scotland's tax-raising and borrowing powers, and is studying devolving control over parts of welfare and social security. Under the Scotland Act 2012, from <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2012/mar/21/scotland-power-set-income-tax-2016\">2016 Scotland will already set its own income tax rate</a>, raising £5.6bn worth of its own spending.</p><p>On Tuesday, the Scottish Tory leader Ruth Davidson joined with senior Scottish Labour and Lib Dem figures by agreeing that Holyrood could get even greater tax powers after 2015.</p><p>Several influential think tanks, including Reform Scotland which has members from all three main UK parties, and the Institute for Public Policy Research, are pushing for greater Scottish control over tax and welfare.</p><p>In Wales, all the parties – including senior figures in the Tory party – are debating seeking more legislative powers, including control over policing, currently reserved to Westminster, and their first powers over tax-raising. The Northern Ireland assembly at Stormont (the UK's longest running devolved legislature) already has wide-ranging, substantial autonomy, but has been pressing for control over corporation tax.</p><p>Observers and insiders alike believe the UK government will delay any action on implementing McKay's recommendations until after next year's Scottish referendum. But that will take Westminster so close to the 2015 general election, the pace and intensity of devolution will speed up. If it does, the West Lothian question and McKay's solution are likely to become more pressing.</p><p><em>Notes: This study is designed to provide a snapshot of MPs' performance, by collecting total figures for MPs from all four parts of the UK. It includes every MP from Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland and compares them to a control group of 100 MPs from English constituencies.</p><p>The debates and parliamentary questions figures come from <a href=\"http://www.theyworkforyou.com/\">theyworkforyou.com</a>. It gathers and stores data only for the previous 365 days. Our data on these two tests covers the 365 days from 1 February 2012.</p><p>This means that in some cases, an individual MP's figures for questions and debates will vary from one day or week to the next: if they placed a large group of questions on the days before or after our 365 day window, their overall figure would change.</p><p>The voting figures come from <a href=\"http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/\">publicwhip.org.uk</a> are a percentage of all votes staged since 25 May 2010, when the current parliament was convened. So this is an absolute number, calculated until 2 February 2013.</em></p><p>• Research by Rebecca Gillard, Camilla Hellum, Remi Labed and Aura Murphy</p><p><a name=\"data\"></p><h2>Download the data</h2><p></a></p><p>• <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0AonYZs4MzlZbdGFidXpnUHR0TUpESHJsbmlKclJFdGc&usp=sharing\">DATA: download the full spreadsheet</a></p><p><strong></strong></p><h2>NEW! Buy our book</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Facts-are-Sacred-Guardian-ebook/dp/B006PI9PQG/\">• Facts are Sacred: the power of data (on Kindle)</a></p><h2>More open data</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data\">Data journalism and data visualisations from the Guardian</a></p><h2>World government data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world-government-data\">Search the world's government data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Development and aid data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store/global-development-data/search?q=\">Search the world's global development data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Can you do something with this data?</h2><p>• <strong>Flickr</strong> Please post your visualisations and mash-ups on our <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/groups/1115946@N24/\">Flickr group</a><br />• Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:data@guardian.co.uk\">data@guardian.co.uk</a></p><p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/page/2009/jun/17/1\">Get the A-Z of data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store\">More at the Datastore directory</a></strong><br /><strong>• <a href=\"http://twitter.com/datastore\">Follow us on Twitter</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/Guardian-data/155291341187950\">Like us on Facebook</a></strong></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/scotland\">Scotland</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/northernireland\">Northern Ireland</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/wales\">Wales</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/conservatives\">Conservatives</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/liberaldemocrats\">Liberal Democrats</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/labour\">Labour</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/snp\">Scottish National party (SNP)</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/sinn-fein\">Sinn Féin</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/severincarrell\">Severin Carrell</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" /><img width='1' height='1' src='http://guardian.co.uk.feedsportal.com/c/34708/f/643782/s/2a09447a/mf.gif' border='0'/><div class='mf-viral'><table border='0'><tr><td valign='middle'><a href=\"http://share.feedsportal.com/viral/sendEmail.cfm?lang=en&title=Devolution+and+Westminster%3A+How+productive+are+non-English+MPs%3F&link=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.guardian.co.uk%2Fnews%2Fdatablog%2F2013%2Fmar%2F27%2Fhow-productive-non-english-mps\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://res3.feedsportal.com/images/emailthis2.gif\" border=\"0\" /></a></td></tr></table></div><br/><br/><a href=\"http://da.feedsportal.com/r/161906992656/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2a09447a/a2.htm\"><img src=\"http://da.feedsportal.com/r/161906992656/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2a09447a/a2.img\" border=\"0\"/></a><img width=\"1\" height=\"1\" src=\"http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/161906992656/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2a09447a/a2t.img\" border=\"0\"/>") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Sinn Féin") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "Northern Ireland") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Scottish National party (SNP)") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Liberal Democrats") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Politics") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "UK news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "Scotland") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Conservatives") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "Wales") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Labour") (pubDate nil "Wed, 27 Mar 2013 08:00:00 GMT") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2013/mar/27/how-productive-non-english-mps") (dc:creator nil "Severin Carrell") (dc:subject nil "News") (dc:date nil "2013-03-27T08:33:28Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "406076290") (media:keywords nil "UK news, Politics, Scotland, Northern Ireland, Wales, Conservatives, Liberal Democrats, Labour, Scottish National party (SNP), Sinn Féin") (media:content ((height . "84") (lang . " ") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/10/20/1319108663694/House-of-Commons-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Dominic Lipinski/PA") (media:description nil "The public services bill is at a critical stage in the House of Commons. Photograph: Dominic Lipinski/PA")) (media:content ((height . "276") (lang . " ") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Politics/Pix/pictures/2010/5/18/1274186237516/A-packed-House-of-Commons-006.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Pa/PA") (media:description nil "A packed House of Commons: now that Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland all have increasing devolution, what role do their MPs play at Westminster? Photograph: Pa"))) (item nil (title nil "Deficit, national debt and government borrowing - how has it changed since 1946?") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2010/oct/18/deficit-debt-government-borrowing-data") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/27974?ns=guardian&pageName=GUK%3AGraphic%3Adeficit-debt-government-borrowing-data%3A1389118&ch=News&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Business%2CGeneral+election+2010%2CEconomic+policy%2CEconomic+growth+%28GDP%29+UK%2CTax+and+spending%2CPublic+finance+%28Society%29%2CSociety%2COffice+for+National+Statistics+ONS%2CGovernment+borrowing%2CUK+news%2CCoalition+Liberal-Conservative+coalition%2CAlistair+Darling%2CPolitics%2CSpending+review+2010%2COffice+for+Budget+Responsibility&c5=Society+Weekly%2CUnclassified%2CPersonal+Finance%2CCredit+Crunch%2CPolicy+Society%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CBusiness+Markets%2CBudget&c6=Julia+Kollewe%2CSimon+Rogers&c7=2010%2F04%2F22+11%3A27&c8=1389118&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Datablog%2CPolitics+blog&c47=UK&c65=Deficit%2C+national+debt+and+government+borrowing+-+how+has+it+changed+since+1946%3F&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FNews%2Fblog%2FDatablog\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">How bad is the deficit really? We bring you all the data going back to the 1940s<br />• <a href=\"#data\">Get the data</a></p><p>How bad is Britain's deficit? The latest set of figures show that Britain's public finances showed <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2013/mar/21/uk-government-borrowing-ons-psnb-4g\">a much smaller than expected deficit</a> in February.</p><p>The<a href=\"http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/psa/public-sector-finances/february-2013/stb---february-2013.html\"> Office for National Statistics said</a> the public sector current budget deficit was £1.1bn in February - this is a £7.1bn lower deficit than the same time last year.</p><p>The Guardian writes today: </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>February's figures are flattered by a known £2.6bn transfer of cash from the Bank of England under a deal to return gilt interest to the government, and £2.3bn from the sale of next-generation mobile phone frequencies.</p><p>But underlying performance was also strong, with a drop in local government spending and stronger central government tax receipts.</p><p>Since the start of the tax year in April 2012, borrowing has totalled £94.9bn, excluding a one-off boost from the transfer of Royal Mail pension assets. This is 8.9% lower than at the same point in the 2011-12 tax year, and with one month left of the fiscal year, Osborne is in a strong position to meet his new full-year goal of borrowing no more than £114.5bn – just over 7% of GDP.</p></blockquote><h2>UK public debt</h2><p><strong></strong></p><p>We have the complete set of data on Government borrowing, all the way back to the 1940s. All political parties have faced their fair share of debt through the years - almost as if the economic climate has its own life independent of who is managing it. </p><p>What is the deficit? When the ONS talks about the deficit, they take a simple measure - the gap between what's coming into the government in taxes and receipts versus what's being spent. Most commentators look at net borrowing as the deficit figure, because it includes investment spending. It's different to the national debt - which is the total the country owes.</p><p>So last month the budget was in deficit. Here are the key facts for November - if you exclude the temporary effects of the financial interventions in the banks:</p><blockquote><p>• Public sector net borrowing was £2.8bn in February 2013; this is a £9bn lower net borrowing than in February 2012, when net borrowing was £11.8bn.<br />• Public sector current budget deficit was £1.1bn in February 2013; this is a £7.1bn lower deficit than in February 2012, when there was a deficit of £8.1bn.<br />• For the period April 2012 to February 2013, public sector net borrowing (excluding the effects of the Royal Mail Pension Plan transfer in April 2012 and the transfers from the Bank of England Asset Purchase Facility) was £101.3bn; this is £2.9bn lower net borrowing than in the same period the previous year, when net borrowing was £104.2bn.<br />• February 2013 public sector net borrowing (PSNB ex) was reduced by £2.7bn as a result of cash transfers from the Bank of England Asset Purchase Facility Fund to Government and by £2.3bn as a result of proceeds from the 4G spectrum auction.<br />• Public sector net debt was £1,161.5bn at the end of February 2013, equivalent to 73.5% of gross domestic product (GDP).<br />• In 2012/13, public sector net borrowing and public sector current budget deficit are reduced by £6.4bn as a result of cash transfers from the Bank of England Asset Purchase Facility Fund to Government.<br />• In 2012/13, public sector net borrowing and public sector net investment are reduced by £28bn as a result of the transfer of the Royal Mail Pension Plan in April 2012.<br /> </p></blockquote><p>The ONS <a href=\"#data\">data below</a> shows monthly, quarterly and annual debt and deficit - what can you do with it?</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><a name=\"data\"></p><h2>Download the data</h2><p></a><br />• <a href=\"https://spreadsheets.google.com/ccc?key=0AonYZs4MzlZbdEdNdWlxdGhJVHE1WE9OYlVQazZUcWc&hl=en\">DATA: download the full list as a spreadsheet</a></p><h2>More data</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data\">More data journalism and data visualisations from the Guardian</a></p><h2>World government data</h2><p><strong></strong></p><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world-government-data\">Search the world's government data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Development and aid data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store/global-development-data/search?q=\">Search the world's global development data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Can you do something with this data?</h2><p>• <strong>Flickr</strong> Please post your visualisations and mash-ups on our <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/groups/1115946@N24/\">Flickr group</a><br />• Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:data@guardian.co.uk\">data@guardian.co.uk</a></p><p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/page/2009/jun/17/1\">Get the A-Z of data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store\">More at the Datastore directory</a></strong><br /><strong>• <a href=\"http://twitter.com/guardiandata\">Follow us on Twitter</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/Guardian-data/155291341187950\">Like us on Facebook</a></strong></p><div class=\"related\"