></a>&nbsp;<a href=\"http://share.feedsportal.com/share/email/?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.guardian.co.uk%2Fnews%2Fdatablog%2F2013%2Fapr%2F16%2Fdata-store-boston-marathon-explosions&t=Boston+explosions%3A+information+and+misinformation\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://res3.feedsportal.com/social/email.png\" border=\"0\" /></a></td></tr></table></div><br/><br/><a href=\"http://da.feedsportal.com/r/163644559736/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2ac774b9/kg/342/a2.htm\"><img src=\"http://da.feedsportal.com/r/163644559736/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2ac774b9/kg/342/a2.img\" border=\"0\"/></a><img width=\"1\" height=\"1\" src=\"http://pi.feedsportal.com/r/163644559736/u/49/f/643782/c/34708/s/2ac774b9/kg/342/a2t.img\" border=\"0\"/>" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2013/apr/16/data-store-boston-marathon-explosions" (20845 17180) old 7 nil nil ((title nil "Boston explosions: information and misinformation") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2013/apr/16/data-store-boston-marathon-explosions") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/58830?ns=guardian&pageName=Graphic%3Adata-store-boston-marathon-explosions%3A1894549&ch=News&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+explosions+%28News%29%2CWorld+news&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Mona+Chalabi%2CJohn+Burn-Murdoch&c7=2013%2F04%2F16+01%3A25&c8=1894549&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=Show+and+Tell+%28dataviz+series%29&c19=GUK&c25=Datablog&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Boston+explosions%3A+information+and+misinformation&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FNews%2Fblog%2FDatablog\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">No arrests have yet been made and no groups have claimed responsibility for the explosions at the Boston marathon. Social media, both good and bad, has filled the information space <br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-news-blog/2013/apr/16/boston-marathon-explosions-hunt-begins-for-perperators-live-updates\">Live updates on Boston marathon explosions from Paul Owen</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/interactive/2013/apr/16/boston-marathon-explosion-map-interactive\">Guardian interactive tool on the blasts</a></p><p>At around 2.50pm ET (7.50pm GMT) two explosions were detonated near the finish line of the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston Marathon</a>. Since then, there has been a frantic attempt to collect and visualise information about events and the number of victims. Here, look at some of the tools used to gain clarity about what happened, assist those seeking help and those providing it.</p><h2>Information</h2><p><a href=\"http://live.boston.com/Event/Live_blog_Explosion_in_Copley_Square/72936164\">Boston.com</a> quickly set up two Google forms in response to the explosion: one '<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/a/guardian.co.uk/forms/d/1r2dbf7q2sIiiQWynPNgH74qNeheNycTyk7hXue9AJhs/viewform\">need a place to stay</a>' and one '<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/a/guardian.co.uk/forms/d/1dqIKVq6IqX4BVXqOW_a9-qmXt1KJ_4Nu3NPNnC1g1mw/viewform\">I have a place to offer</a>'. Users were also able to see the information already submitted by others, including phone numbers and e-mail addresses so that they could contact others directly.</p><p>Using <a href=\"http://www.tableausoftware.com/\">Tableau</a>, we've shown how the number of offers of accommodation has changed over time as the link to the spreadsheet was shared on social media, news and official websites. The graph shows how in the space of two minutes, the number of offers increased from 3 to 85 and stayed high over the next ten minutes. This peaked again around an hour later, when 33 offers to help those needing shelter were received via Google. </p><p>As has been the case in the aftermath of other crises (such as the Mumbai attacks in 2011), social media has played a central role. Boston's mayor's office quickly tweeted information about which areas to avoid and Boston's police department used its twitter account to request information from members of the public, announce street closures and press conferences.</p><p>In fact, not tweeting was a decision which had to be <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BostonFire\">publicly justified</a> by Boston's fire department.</p><p><a href=\"http://trendsmap.com/\">Trendsmap</a> tracks twitter trends in real time and maps them using the location in users' twitter profiles. As it's so soon after the event, several of these visualisations are still being developed, however as this <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BlL-foAGizk&feature=player_embeddedhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BlL-foAGizk&feature=player_embedded\">video after the Samoa earthquake demonstrates</a>, Trendsmap is also able to show how twitter trends evolve over time.</p><p>Because it can process tweets in all languages, Trendsmap can also show global twitter trends. These screengrabs (taken at 11am GMT) show that the Boston marathon explosion was not just the main topic of American twitter users, but also those in Western Europe, South Africa, Australia, East Asia and the Middle East.</p><p>Maps have also been important in order to understand the impact of the explosion at the micro-level. This interactive map developed by The Guardian shows where the devices were detonated and includes verified pictures taken after the blasts. </p><p><strong></strong></p><h2>Misinformation</h2><p>Inevitably, a small number of opportunists have sought to use the explosions to further their own agendas. A twitter account promising a $1 donation to victims for every retweet received more than 50,000 retweets and 800 favourites before being <a href=\"http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2013/04/15/fake-boston-marathon-twitter-account-appears-after-explosions-quickly-suspended/\">suspended</a> by Twitter. Another account, <a href=\"https://twitter.com/HopeForBoston?tw_i=323948385952473088&tw_p=tweetembed\">@HopeforBoston</a>, claims to have images of children killed in Boston's explosions who were running for victims of last year's <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/newtown-shooting\">Newtown shooting</a>. Despite receiving more than 100,000 retweets, the images are fake and were taken from a <a href=\"http://www.saxonscope.com/top-stories/2012/05/20/hundreds-turn-out-for-3rd-annual-joe-cassella-5k/\">school run</a> in May last year.</p><h2>More open data</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data\">Data journalism and data visualisations from the Guardian</a></p><h2>World government data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world-government-data\">Search the world's government data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Development and aid data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store/global-development-data/search?q=\">Search the world's global development data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Can you do something with this data?</h2><p>• <strong>Flickr</strong> Please post your visualisations and mash-ups on our <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/groups/1115946@N24/\">Flickr group</a><br />• Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:data@guardian.co.uk\">data@guardian.co.uk</a></p><p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/page/2009/jun/17/1\">Get the A-Z of data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store\">More at the Datastore directory</a></strong><br /><strong>• <a href=\"http://twitter.com/GuardianData\">Follow us on Twitter</a></strong><br /><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/Guardian-data/155291341187950\">Like us on Facebook</a></strong></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon explosions</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/mona-chalabi\">Mona Chalabi</a></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/john-burn-murdoch\">John Burn-Murdoc