 <a href=\"#data\">Download the data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data\">More data journalism and data visualisations from the Guardian</a></p><p>Whether it was 'space', 'investment', 'safety' or quite simply 'contentment', homes in East London report the lowest levels of happiness in the UK according to research published today by property website<a href=\"http://www.rightmove.co.uk/news/articles/rightmove-news/happy-at-home-index-london\"> Rightmove</a>. </p><p>The survey of almost 40,000 people also found that nine of the 10 'unhappiest' places to live were to be found in Greater London. Harrogate in Yorkshire came top of the list as the <a href=\"http://www.guprod.gnl/news/datablog/2013/mar/27/uk-towns-happiness-ranking\">'happiest town' to live in in the UK</a>.</p><p>Carlisle, which was considered the happiest town in 2012 has since dropped to 19th place. Meanwhile, towns in Greater London continue to languish at the bottom of the chart. East London, which received the lowest score in 2012, again had the fewest respondents reporting happiness in 2013. </p><p><strong>How do you define happiness?</strong></p><p>Rightmove's <a href=\"http://www.rightmove.co.uk/news/files/2013/03/Rightmove-Happy-At-Home-Index-2013.pdf\">approach</a> was to ask people in 110 UK towns to what extent they agreed with 12 statements ranging from 'I often feel unsafe in the community in which I live' to 'I do not worry about the value of my property'. </p><p>But not all of the statements in the survey necessarily reflect upon towns. For example, the first statement 'on the whole, the décor and furnishings in my home are to my liking' might be more indicative of the socio-economic background of the individual completing the survey, than of the town under scrutiny. As it turns out, Cleveland in the North East comes top for residents satisfaction with their own décor, but ranks 64th overall in the index. </p><p>Similarly, a negative response to the statement 'generally, I feel relaxed when I am at home' may say more about family life than the town in which the respondent lives. Here again, the correlation between this response and the overall results is relatively weak. </p><p>Harrogate which comes first overall, ranks in 79th place for residents feeling relaxed at home. It is also not clear whether the 40,000 respondents were drawn in equal measure for the 110 towns included in the survey. Clearly, if five people were asked their views on Stockport (2nd place) and 1,000 people were asked about their homes in Croydon (109th place), the findings would be highly skewed. </p><p>There was however a strong correlation between responses on 'neighbourliness' (captured by Rightmove in the statement 'I enjoy spending time in the area in which I live') and a town's overall score. In Greater London where the lowest scores were recorded, respondents were inclined to strongly disagree with this statement.</p><p>Do you agree with these rankings for your town? Contribute to the debate by adding your comments below. You can download the full results from the spreadsheet.</p><h2>Data summary</h2><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a name=\"data\"></p><h2>Download the data</h2><p></a></p><p>• <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0At6CC4x_yBnMdGRMZVdlbV9HM3BqVFJHMlFSOF82bkE&usp=sharing\">DATA: download the full spreadsheet</a><br /><strong>• SOURCE: </strong><a href=\"http://www.rightmove.co.uk/news/articles/rightmove-news/happy-at-home-index-2013\">Rightmove</a></p><h2>NEW! Buy our book</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.guardianbookshop.co.uk/BerteShopWeb/viewProduct.do?ISBN=9780571301614&INTCMP=mic_929\">• Facts are Sacred: the power of data </a></p><h2>More open data</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data\">Data journalism and data visualisations from the Guardian</a></p><h2>World government data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world-government-data\">Search the world's government data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Development and aid data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store/global-development-data/search?q=\">Search the world's global development data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Can you do something with this data?</h2><p>• <strong>Flickr</strong> Please post your visualisations and mash-ups on our <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/groups/1115946@N24/\">Flickr group</a><br />• Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:data@guardian.co.uk\">data@guardian.co.uk</a></p><p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/page/2009/jun/17/1\">Get the A-Z of data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store\">More at the Datastore directory</a></strong><br /><strong>• <a href=\"http://twitter.com/GuardianData\">Follow us on Twitter</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/Guardian-data/155291341187950\">Like us on Facebook</a></strong></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/property\">Property</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/happiness-indices\">Happiness indices</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/rightmove\">Rightmove</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/mona-chalabi\">Mona Chalabi</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" /><img width='1' height='1' src='http://guardian.co.uk.feedsportal.com/c/34708/f/643782/s/2a0e0128/mf.gif' border='0'/><div class='mf-viral'><table border='0'><tr><td valign='middle'><a href=\"http://share.feedsportal.com/viral/sendEmail.cfm?lang=en&title=Homes+in+East+London+are+%27unhappi