008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "David Levene/David Levene") (media:description nil "East London has been named the 'unhappiest' place in the UK in a survey measuring how the British public feels about where they live. Photograph: David Levene")))) ("UK GDP since 1955" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/35473?ns=guardian&pageName=Graphic%3Agdp-uk-1948-growth-economy%3A1176842&ch=Business&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Economic+growth+%28GDP%29+UK%2CEconomic+policy%2CEconomics+%28Business%29%2CQuantitative+easing+%28Business%29%2CFinancial+crisis+%28Business%29%2CBusiness%2CUK+news%2CGovernment+data+%28Politics%29%2COffice+for+National+Statistics+ONS%2CGeneral+election+2010&c5=Credit+Crunch%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CBusiness+Markets&c6=Simon+Rogers&c7=2009%2F03%2F09+05%3A00&c8=1176842&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Datablog&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=UK+GDP+since+1955&c66=Business&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FBusiness%2FBusiness%2FEconomic+growth+%28GDP%29\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Gross domestic product is the economic output of Britain. See how it has changed over time<br />• <a href=\"#data\">Get the data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/interactive/2012/sep/27/recessions-compared-1930-2008\">Interactive chart: How does this recession compare?</a><br />• <a href=\"#chart\">Chart: GDP change since 2008</a></p><p><strong></strong></p><p>The possibility of a triple-dip recession seems to have inched closer as GDP for the last three months of 2012 was confirmed to have dropped by 0.3%. If the economy shrinks again in the first quarter of this year, that will plunge the UK into its third recession in the past five years, an unprecedented triple-dip.</p><p>You can find out who gets <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2012/oct/25/pre-release-access-good-news-david-cameron\">access to this data early too by clicking here.</a></p><p>The ONS explains the data as follows:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p><br />• Household final consumption expenditure increased by 0.4% in volume terms in the latest quarter revised up from the 0.2% increase previously estimated<br />• Among the main contributors to the decrease in GDP in the latest quarter were gross fixed capital formation which fell by 0.2% in volume terms and the £6.0 billion net trade deficit, which follows a £5.3 billion net trade deficit in the previous quarter<br />• GDP in volume terms increased by 0.2% when comparing the fourth quarter of 2012 with the fourth quarter of 2011. Between the years 2011 and 2012, GDP in volume terms increased by 0.3%<br />• The households' saving ratio was estimated to be 7.1% in 2012, the highest since the 1997 estimate of 8.1%<br />• Real household disposable income increased by 2.1% between 2011 and 2012. This is the highest growth since 2003 when it rose by 2.7%<br />• The largest contributions to the increases in the households' saving ratio and real household disposable income were an estimated £20.1 billion increase in wages and salaries in 2012 compared with 2011</p></blockquote><p>A technical recession is defined as two or more consecutive quarters of economic decline. That means the UK is now on course for its third recession in four years.<a name=\"chart\"></a></p><p>The data we have gathered shows percentage change in GDP going back to 1955 by quarter, we have a spreadsheet to download that shows GDP in cash, ie what it was that year not adjusted for inflation, total inflation-adjusted figures and per capita inflation adjusted figures.</p><p>The figures show how recessions compare - thanks to the <a href=\"http://www.niesr.ac.uk/\">National Institute of Economic and Social Research</a> for the data.</p><p>As several of our posters below have pointed out, there's <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2009/mar/24/g20-economics\">more to life than GDP</a> – but here are the latest GDP figures from the ONS for you to explore.</p><h2>Data summary</h2><p><strong></strong></p><p><a name=\"data\"></p><h2>Download the full data</h2><p></a></p><p><a href=\"http://spreadsheets.google.com/ccc?key=phNtm3LmDZEO_Y5Udz-7uSw\">DATA: UK GDP since 1948</a></p><p>• SOURCE: <a href=\"http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/gva/gross-domestic-product--preliminary-estimate/q4-2012/tsd---preliminary-estimate-of-gdp-q4-2012.html\">ONS</a></p><h2>More data</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data\">More data journalism and data visualisations from the Guardian</a></p><h2>World government data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world-government-data\">Search the world's government data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Development and aid data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store/global-development-data/search?q=\">Search the world's global development data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Can you do something with this data?</h2><p>• <strong>Flickr</strong> Please post your visualisations and mash-ups on our <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/groups/1115946@N24/\">Flickr group</a><br />• Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:data@guardian.co.uk\">data@guardian.co.uk</a></p><p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/page/2009/jun/17/1\">Get the A-Z of data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store\">More at the Datastore directory</a></strong><br /><strong>• <a href=\"http://twitter.com/guardiandata\">Follow us on Twitter</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/Guardian-data/155291341187950\">Like us on Facebook</a></strong></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/economicgrowth\">Economic growth (GDP)</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/economy\">Economic policy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/economics\">Economics</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/quantita